[0.004, "o", "\u001b[H;opcache.restrict_api=\r\n\u001b[67X\u001b[3;3HMapping base of shared memory segments (for Windows only). All the PHP\u001b[4;2H processes have to map shared memory into the same address space. This\r\n; directive allows to manually fix the \"Unable to reattach to base address\"\u001b[6;3Herrors.\u001b[66X\u001b[7;2Hopcache.mmap_base=\u001b[55X\r\n\u001b[46X\u001b[9;2H Facilitates multiple OPcache instances per user (for Windows only). All PHP\r\n; processes with the same cache ID and user share an OPcache instance.\u001b[11;2Hopcache.cache_id=\u001b[44X\r\n\u001b[26X\n; Enables and sets the second level cache directory.\u001b[14;4Ht should improve performance when SHM memory is full, at server restart or\u001b[15;3HSHM reset. The default \"\" disables file based caching.\u001b[16;10Hfile_cache=    \u001b[18;3HEnables or disables read-only mode for the second level cache directory.  \u001b[19;3HIt should improve performance for read-only containers,\u001b[22X\u001b[20;4Hhen the cache is pre-warmed and packaged alongside the application.\u001b[21;2H Best used with `opcache.validate_timestamps=0`, `opcache.enable_file_override=1`\r\n; and `opcache.file_cache_consistency_checks=0`.\u001b[23;3HNote: A cache generated with a different build of PHP, a different file path,\u001b[24;2H or different settings (including which \u001b[30m\u001b[103mextension\u001b[m\u000fs are loaded), may be ignored.\r\n;opcache.file_cache_read_only=0\r\n\u001b[71X\u001b[27;3HEnables or disables opcode caching in shared memory.\u001b[28;10Hfile_cache_only=0\u001b[12X\u001b[30;2H Enables or disables checksum validation when script loaded from file cache.\r\n;opcache.file_cache_consistency_checks=1\r\n\u001b[65X\u001b[33;3HImplies opcache.file_cache_only=1 for a certain process that failed to  \u001b[34;3Hreattach to the shared memory (for Windows only). Explicitly enabled file\u001b[35;3Hcache is required.\u001b[50X\u001b[36;2Hopcache.file_cache_fallback=1\u001b[43X\r\n\u001b[70X\u001b[38;2H Enables or disables copying of PHP code (text segment) into HUGE PAGES.\r\n; Under certain circumstances (if only a single global PHP process is\u001b[40;3Hstarted from which all others fork), this can increase performance\u001b[5X\u001b[41;3Hby a tiny amount because TLB misses are reduced.  On the other hand, this\u001b[42;2H delays PHP startup, increases memory usage and degrades performance\r\n; under memory pressure - use with care.\u001b[44;3HRequires appropriate OS configuration.\u001b[37X\u001b[45;2Hopcache.huge_code_pages=0\r\n\u001b[34X\u001b[47;155H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f85,42        96\u001b[48;11H\u001b[?25h"]
